```protobuf
message User {
  string name = 1;
  int32 age = 2;
  repeated string tags = 3;
  map<string, string> metadata = 4;
  optional string bio = 5;
}
```
**message** defines structured data. Field numbers (1, 2, etc.) are used in binary encoding - never reuse deleted numbers.

```protobuf
service UserService {
  rpc GetUser(GetUserRequest) returns (User);
  rpc ListUsers(ListUsersRequest) returns (stream User);  // server stream
  rpc Upload(stream Chunk) returns (UploadResponse);      // client stream
  rpc Chat(stream Msg) returns (stream Msg);              // bidirectional
}
```
**service** defines gRPC endpoints. Four patterns: unary, server streaming, client streaming, bidirectional.

```protobuf
enum Status {
  STATUS_UNSPECIFIED = 0;  // must have 0 value
  STATUS_ACTIVE = 1;
  STATUS_INACTIVE = 2;
}
```
**enum** defines named constants. The zero value is required and should be UNSPECIFIED. Use the type name as prefix convention.

```protobuf
message Example {
  string name = 1;   // 1-15: one byte (use for frequent fields)
  int32 count = 2;   // 16-2047: two bytes
  // 19000-19999: reserved by protobuf

  reserved 5, 10 to 12;          // reserve deleted field numbers
  reserved "old_field_name";     // reserve deleted field names
}
```
**Field numbers** identify fields in the binary format. Use 1-15 for frequently-used fields (more efficient encoding). Never reuse numbers.

```protobuf
import "google/protobuf/timestamp.proto";
import "google/protobuf/duration.proto";
import "google/protobuf/empty.proto";
import "google/protobuf/wrappers.proto";
import "google/protobuf/any.proto";
import "google/protobuf/struct.proto";
```
**Well-known types** are pre-defined utility messages. Timestamp for dates, Empty for no-data responses, wrappers for nullable scalars.
